# FER SM - Bestinver Securities - 11 May 2026
HOLD maintained. 1Q26 call confirms Ferrovial's US toll-road pricing power is holding up even as traffic softens.

## What changed
No estimate revisions in this note — it's a conference-call takeaways piece, not an estimates update. Rating and TP unchanged.

| | 2025E | 2026E |
|---|---|---|
| PE (x) | 52.6 | 66.7 |
| EV/EBITDA (x) | 26.0 | 24.2 |
| FCF Yield (%) | (1.3) | 3.0 |
| Net debt/EBITDA (x) | 4.3 | 3.7 |

Rating: **HOLD**, TP €52.4–56.9 (last price €59.82).

## Why it changed, and why now
Management framed the quarter as pricing power offsetting soft volumes: US managed-lane revenue-per-transaction growth came from tech-enabled vehicle identification/pricing and higher mandatory-mode usage, while weather and construction hurt traffic, especially at NTE (p.2). Gasoline-price sensitivity at 407 ETR is being watched but not yet quantified — March traffic there grew only +1.1% YoY (p.2). 407 ETR's dividend hike was framed as an operating-strength signal, though leverage is now above 2x and no further-year guidance was given (p.2).

Growth pipeline: managed-lane bid decisions expected in Tennessee (late August) and Georgia (mid-October) (p.2). No penalties are expected on JFK New Terminal One construction delays, and any dividend-policy update is now pushed to early 2027 (p.2). Bestinver's take: the highways business's pricing momentum should continue, but sustained fuel-price rises are the risk to monitor (p.2).

