# ACX SM - Bestinver Securities - 11 May 2026
Rating **UNDER REVIEW**. 1Q26 EBITDA landed just below consensus on a sharp HPA contraction, but Acerinox guides to a QoQ improvement in 2Q26E.

## What changed
1Q26E vs. internal consensus (€m):

| Metric | 1Q26 | 1Q26E Consensus | 4Q25 (QoQ) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Sales | 1,384 | 1,547 | +6% |
| EBITDA | 95 | 110 | +192% |
| EBIT | 45 | 60 | n/a |
| Net Profit | 5 | 29 | n/a |
| Net Debt | 1,295 | 1,282 | +9% |

EBITDA came in below the €110m internal consensus, though sharply up QoQ from €32m in 4Q25 (p.4-5).

## Why it changed, and why now
Sales rose 6% QoQ to €1.38bn on a price recovery and +22% QoQ melting-shop volumes, despite weaker apparent demand (-11% US, -7% Europe) that was offset by lower imports under new regulation (p.4). Stainless EBITDA improved as expected on higher prices, but the negative surprise was HPAs, where EBITDA fell 60% QoQ on O&G/chemical-processing weakness tied to geopolitical instability (p.4); EBITDA also included a €25m inventory adjustment, split roughly €15m from European stainless pass-through lag and €10m from HPA/O&G exposure (p.6). Net debt rose €106m QoQ on working-capital outflow, dividends and capex (p.4).

For 2Q26E, management guides to higher EBITDA QoQ on better order books and lower imports, and expects only a limited Iran-war impact (c.-€2m on March EBITDA), citing its energy-hedging strategy (p.4). On the call, management also confirmed it's exploring a potential US listing/IPO while retaining a controlling stake, with no final decision yet; Europe is targeted to reach break-even in 3Q26E (not 2Q26E), and capacity utilisation currently stands at ~80% US / ~70% Europe / ~60-65% South Africa (p.6).

